how do I git log from head and to a specific commit?
To view the Git log from the HEAD (current commit) to a specific commit, you can use the following command:

```
git log HEAD...<commit-hash>
```

Here's how to use it:

1. Replace `<commit-hash>` with the hash of the specific commit you want to log to.

2. The `..` (two dots) notation specifies a range of commits, from the commit after the one specified on the left side up to and including the one on the right side.

3. Since HEAD is the current commit, this will show all commits from the current state back to (but not including) the specified commit.

Examples:

1. To see logs from HEAD to a specific commit:
   ```
   git log HEAD...abc123
   ```

2. You can also use branch names or other references:
   ```
   git log HEAD...main
   git log HEAD...origin/main
   ```

3. To include the specified commit in the log, use two dots instead of three:
   ```
   git log HEAD..abc123
   ```

4. To customize the output, you can add formatting options:
   ```
   git log --oneline HEAD...abc123
   ```

5. To see the changes in each commit:
   ```
   git log -p HEAD...abc123
   ```

Remember, you can always use `git log --help` to see all available options for the log command.


